body:
@developerChans, QLinearAdd on x86 uses 'round to nearest, ties to even' but uses 'round to nearest, ties to up' on arm. As you tested on the x86, I think the numeric difference (98.50000716 in our c program vs 98.5 in ORT) comes from the computation order. We compute the fixed part firstly. Here is how QLinearAdd computed in ORT. Could you please alternate your C program in same computing order and see if you can get same result?

https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/blob/62551946593382489b1f3dc4187adc0838ed472b/onnxruntime/core/mlas/lib/intrinsics/avx2/qladd_avx2.cpp#L116

You roundNum implementation is not right. it actually round x.5 up, not to even. Please use this function:
https://en.cppreference.com/w/c/numeric/math/nearbyint

issue.body:
# Ask a Question

### Question

[QuantizeLinear ](https://github.com/onnx/onnx/blob/main/docs/Operators.md#QuantizeLinear)

I had a question about operator while using onnx . In operator QuantizeLinear's description, "For (x / y_scale), it's rounding to nearest ties to even." There is an explanation. The 'Rounding Rule' in this syntax is difficult to understand because I have never encountered it. You ask how the 'Rounding Rule' should be applied.

body:
137.499992 is less than 137.5 and should be rounded to 137. 137.5 will be rounded to 138, so OnnxRuntime's result is correct. 
Please note that the rounding rule is "round to nearest, ties to even". for 137.499992, its nearest integer is 137, so it will be rounded to 137. For 137.5, its nearest integers are 137 and 138 (tie). Then round to even(138).

Thank you. @yufenglee  I solved the problem in the following way. First, the rounding rule was modified through nearbyintf, and finally, it was converted from calculating in 32-bit to calculating in 64-bit format. For decimal arithmetic, I think 64-bit arithmetic should be preferred.
